"Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+5+8]&lt;br&gt;→ Wild insects (humane pesticides)&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 5 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJyFlm1v4jgQx7%2FKCN3qoKI0wLJqOfGiD%2FRBy95WXe5Wp1KlJpkQ3zp2ZDukuW6%2F%2B44TSqEE3aumnfHP8%2FCfcZ8bIUYsE%2FZchdgYNo6OYDQawVQzLsEqCDT7r6CPXMIs63ndj5ArLcIlxxzyrt%2Fz%2B%2F7AP4amsSqF45Y7PJMEOTUmS1LLlYQgJtYQPEiZVkHMmXCo7kkPuhAx7bOcFX6cJUyaV0MPmOQJE8Y3KsE8ZvbV0ocos5nG1QE%2FYdai9nNuYz%2FkJlCZtFwuXt0Ha9DKkflCrWHHINH6EhfM8iX6lasv6NuUSYxZEAN7y4QbYHBb2Ji%2BIy4QqEZvZnME1kXKwtC0QSMVlks0oHQJ03hIBWAJUhjc0N9tjFVtfjeUlAxKxh8QqCRVxuWwdqCzMkQi0p94FZqxTIZMKImQUOdEBx7XjRkvH12o7jg%2BpRhYOrhkIkNQUUl462GnhJ2hsTDPCsjcNe6gwc3EhvCdi5CyNQQz0Cxrj5DSMR7wEE2r4lyN%2FxzfnU7HFzAvYIESNbPYSYtX6WDI7VbBDsjYBkkdKcNyNSVSybrgmi4DjCL3gwqOrhlKL6haqaZG6QLmdEVEEdB3G87Gl1%2FvxlQNzURJyJEvYicGqo1QTswxf6x6KNRCKk3NhhPvA5zfQFNpyvxQRYcJW0husxDh7Ot0fO4yMypLP3MbxCgvmChuUf9lQh